\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Neural Network Fundamentals — notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formlly, a neural network is defined by the function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{\left[l\right]}=\begin{cases}
g^{\left[0\right]}\left(x\right) & l=0\\
g^{\left[l\right]}\left(W^{\left[l-1\right]}a^{\left[l-1\right]}+b^{\left[l\right]}\right) & l>0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{y}=a^{\left[L\right]}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a vector of real numbers representing some input given to the model,
 called the 
\emph on
input layer
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is an ordered series of vectors of varying, predetermined lengths, called
 
\emph on
layers
\emph default
, each containing real numbers, called its
\emph on
 neurons
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the toal number of layers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is a sereis of matrices totalling 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, each of which is called 
\emph on
weights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is an ordered series of vectors of real numbers totalling 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, where each vector is called a 
\emph on
bias vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is an ordered series of functions, called 
\emph on
activation functions, 
\emph default
totalling 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, such that each function is defined 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, and maps each value of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector to a new 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector by applying some constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R\to\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

 function on each of its values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 is a layer index, starting from 0, such that: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\left[l\right]}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $l\text{th}$
\end_inset

 layer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\left[l\right]}$
\end_inset

 is a weights matrix columns for each neuron in 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\left[l\right]}$
\end_inset

 and rows for each neuron in 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\left[l+1\right]}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $b^{\left[l\right]}$
\end_inset

 is a bias vector with a length identical to 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\left[l\right]}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\left[l\right]}$
\end_inset

 is an activation function 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the length of 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\left[l\right]}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of real numbers, representing the output of the model, called
 the 
\emph on
output layer
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
More Intuitively
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Visually, a neural network is represnted via the following imagery:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename .visual/basic_model.jpeg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each circle in here is represented by a real number, and is called a neuron.
 Each column of neurons is called a layer, and is represented by some vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{\left[l\right]}=\begin{bmatrix}a_{1}^{\left[l\right]}\\
a_{2}^{\left[l\right]}\\
\vdots\\
a_{n}^{\left[l\right]}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the numbers of neurons in the layer.
 As a rule of thumb 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}^{\left[l\right]}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $k\text{th}$
\end_inset

 neuron in the 
\begin_inset Formula $l\text{th}$
\end_inset

 layer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a general rule, we give the model some input vector 
\color green

\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\color inherit
 (for example, a list of greyscale values for each pixel of an image),
\color green
 
\color inherit
and that becomes the first layer (
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\left[0\right]}$
\end_inset

).
 The last layer, 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\left[L\right]}$
\end_inset

, is the output of the model, a vector 
\color blue

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 
\color inherit
(for example, each number can match a category—car, train, et cetera—and
 represent the probability the image contains it).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the layers between 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\left[0\right]}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{\left[l\right]}$
\end_inset

 is how we get from 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

, and we can think of it as some function 
\color orange

\begin_inset Formula $f\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with some input vector 
\color green

\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\color inherit
.
 This can be, for example, a list of greyscale values for each pixel of
 an image.
\end_layout

\end_body
